rwise familiar scenes of overload boredom: texting, browsing social media, and performing information work. Ultimately, she shows that the opposite of boredom is not interest but meaning, and that we can only make it by curating the overload.The Spiritual Significance of Overload Boredom is a bold and original intervention for the present condition, unsettling the framing of existing work around technological modernity and its discontents.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAesthetics. 0aArts. 0aBoredom. 0aCaringxMoral and ethical aspects. 0aMeaning (Philosophy). 0aTechnologyxPsychological aspects. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Aesthetics.2bisacsh  aDavid Foster Wallace.  aaddiction.  aaesthetics.  aaffect.  aakedia.  aalgorithms.  aart history.  acare.  achoice.  acomputers.  aconceptual art.  aconnection.  acontemplation.  acontemporary culture.  acuration.  adependence.  adigital banal.  adisaffect.  adistraction.  aentropy.  aethics.  aeveryday.  aexistential despair.  afiction.  ahabit.  ainformation.  ainterface.  akedia.  alate modernity.  aliterature.  ameaning.  ameditation.  amental life.  anew media.  anoise.  aontology.  aphilosophy.  apsychic pain.  aritual.  ascreens.  asecularization.  asensory overload.  asocial media.  aspeculative realism.  aspiritual crisis.  asubjectivity.  atechnology.  atexting.  atime.  awithdrawal.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311127214608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2022z978311127419540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978022801329740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780228013297423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780228013297/original  a978-3-11-127214-6  ACUP C